Barack Obama is the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama is coming to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma, the medal and a check of over $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the northern metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he pays a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October out of 172 people and 33 organizations.
The pair then met with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit culminates with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the Prestige Award.
He is the fourth president of the United States, but only the third to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already warned that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when taking the prize.
The president does not want to evade this issue because he knows that he is taking over the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He intensified the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, the diploma and the cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event programme then includes a banquet with the President and his wife, which will include the Prime Minister and 250 other invited guests, apart from the King and Queen of Norway.
Obama was very cautious about the price from the beginning.
For example, he suggested that he felt that he did not fully deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that the price is not only for him, but for all who aspire to the same values as he.
Immediately after the announcement, he said that for him this was a "call to action".
