Czech discovery: a substance that also works in ‘stealed’ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works in the viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact predominates against the disadvantage that the compound does not act as strongly on common virus variants as one of the already existing drugs.
The AIDS disease cannot be cured yet.
However, the composition of the drug can prolong the life of the patient and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of the virus multiplication has also resulted in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no more drugs are effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical and Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg paves the way for dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metallocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block viral propagation in ways other than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come up with new ‘improved’ compounds, which have been prepared based on knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
The metallocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus cleavage caused by the HIV protease, no mature viral particles would be produced.
If we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the virus’s propagation in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper, published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed further.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the test tube, including against their persistent (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallocarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the drugs used clinically, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formations, makes the metallocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Institute of Biochemistry of the Institute for Organic Chemistry of the Institute of Structural Biology.
