Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the industrialized countries, such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A step-by-step relaxation
Enshrined in the country’s 1978 constitution, China’s one-child policy is arguably the most controversial provision introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy will face huge fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplaces.
Chinese state representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of the country’s natural resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to abort.
Many couples also had sex-selective abortions performed, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their stance on one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including urban dwellers, members of ethnic minorities and cases where both husband and wife have been single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute for Population Research at the University of Beijing, said government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples with two children who are single.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city administration has sent out city employees and family planning volunteers to look for couples at home and to push information sheets under the doors.
