Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said there was a surge in requests from couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, urban districts do not report any change.
In the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are still received per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say the number of births in the city expected for 2010 will still be around 165,000 despite the campaign -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai municipality of Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
