The schizophrenic is at the center of the event, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he becomes in a passive role, he is overwhelmed by the events, similar to in the dream, and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A balance of reality is usually not possible for them, the deceptions are cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Having experienced a hallucination once in your life
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real context.
Why exactly our brain strikes caprioles, researchers are still figuring out.
Exceptional conditions can cause any person to lose the relationship to reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the determining factors alone.
Researchers believe that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, for example, explains Fox.
But there remains a mystery as to how the disorder of the neural system comes about, which at first does not manifest itself over many years.
Environmental influences also play a role – stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains are hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive medications to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get them, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether fake images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a question of position.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and deceptions for ten years, last year he evaluated his results in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are one of the typical symptoms of psychosis, but also of surprisingly many other diseases.
These include, in addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, often also diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and cranial trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain of healthy people hallucinates.
Hallucinations, so box, are composed of memory contents that are usually retained.
They arise when areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain runs hot or even when there is a lack of stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But it is also deprivation of attraction, stress, love anxiety or other mental states of emergency.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attending high school there.
A very normal girl, actually.
If it weren’t for the pictures and the voices.
In the break, it can happen that a sluggish boy with long, dark hair appeals to it.
When it responds to him, the classmates look at it in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spunky daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn’t dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a moment.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she wonders sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other fake pictures are not real and disappear again.
At night, the appearances are usually frightening
Often the deceptions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she can sometimes not follow the teaching material, because the teacher is just introducing a new classmate in her eyes and ears, while he explains mathematical equations to everyone else on the board.
At night, the symptoms are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which comes much too rarely and much too late, she often can’t tell whether she’s awake or already dreaming, whether the images she sees are the frowns or the girl with the bleeding cuts to her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she yells at the figures.
Parents and friends don’t tell her anything that would make her crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She passed the Abitur last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she made contact with the psychologist’s box on the Internet, she knows exactly that she’s not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of desperation
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from stimulus withdrawal, they are most likely to have hallucinations after a while, Kasten says.
I suspect the brain is then underemployed and provides its own entertainment.
Sarah K., a single child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she’s called dad has not been her physical father since she can think.
Because visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to differentiate between fake images and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "is in the brain, reality is formed there.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
Even nocturnal dream pictures value box as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their falsehoods as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
Border state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our world that is too conscious, imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and head of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative – madness is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dreamlike altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers to be real and that he cannot distinguish from the waking state even in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis at full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self- and world loss, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is present in the imagination.
An intense form of sense-founding and meaning-making in an inherently unbearable situation that allows us humans our own creative ability not to sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Change" as a saving action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after heart valve surgery followed by heart transplant, while his body is doomed to immobility at the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-made world, visits foreign times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who produce drugs from blood.
Dragged by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snowy Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
It goes on completely in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different for Claussen from any dream.
Dream is another state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories of mental journeys are still unclear to me after years and in secondary details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience blows the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug cravings show how fragile our inner images of outer reality are also in waking.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist’s box, “can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.”
An experience that can also be enriching.
