75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fertility and Career of Women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between 15 and 75 years of age leaves no doubt: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited by their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and if so, what kind of profession they pursue.
Those of them who do not do any other work outside the house, work only half-days or do not have a fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a fixed job, especially in the public sector, postpone the founding of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a fixed employment get their first child on average only 3.7 years after contracting, a figure that increases to 4.1 years for women with a fixed employment, who have taken longer to achieve this and who have their contracting and the first child only realized much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a major impact on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of willingness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be seen in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between the ages of 35 and 49, depending on whether they only have a primary school diploma or a higher education, became mothers for the first time with an average of 25.1 or 32.1 each.
There is also a further difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with major degrees get married before their first fixed-term employment and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree do it exactly differently and first look for a fixed-term employment and then get married after that and then have their first child, notes Delgado.
