Support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system back then and as is the case with the ESP stability control, the auxiliary braking systems for emergency braking have to become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly authorised passenger cars and light vans, with a waiting period until the end of February 2011 for the remaining vehicles.
The decision taken by the European Union is aimed at improving the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many on-road accidents because of their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects on the brake pedal on the basis of the braking force executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - one expects that one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
