How much should you earn on your Facebook profile?
Facebook users can now find out their salary, thanks to the new application Trovit, the search engine with the most ads of real estate, job offers and cars in Spain, that they should earn due to their profile.
The "How Much Should You Earn?" tool calculates users' salaries based on more than 140,000 vacancies available at Trovit in Spain. Users are provided with a form on Facebook that allows them to enter their profession, work experience, age and the city in which they work.
Just a week after the application was first available, the search engine found that the Spanish worker on average "feels poorly paid," Trovit's product manager, Albert Ribera, explains in a press release.
The Spaniards are the lowest paid according to the data Trovit has through its search engines in the UK and France.
A British programmer gets a gross annual salary of 45,226 euros and a French 31,059, as opposed to the 24,000 euros a Spaniard earns.
Accordingly, a truck driver has a net annual salary of 34,247 euros in England, 25,751 in France and 16,420 euros in Spain.
According to Trovit, the lowest paid work in Spain is that of a waiter with an annual net of 11,592 euros; followed by the work of a salesman with 14,725 euros and that of a worker with 15,667 euros.
The most searched jobs on the Internet in the last three months are those of a driver, half-day jobs and social workers.
