New programmes for the assessment of vehicles
In these days of storms and accidents, not only the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed into the workshops, where an appraiser must assess the damage and the cost of repair.
No single accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a matter of minutes
That’s why almost 100% of reviewers use these types of systems.
The service and application providers for the evaluation of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from the manufacturers to process it and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are created with its products.
The other two companies that compete with the market for reviewing and drafting a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that manufacturers provide is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Vel<0xC3><0xA1>zquez, sales manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each providing the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is increasing, to the point that in the last five years even more versions, variants and motorizations came on the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car arrives on the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a cumbersome task, because each and every one of the over a thousand vehicle parts must be catalogized and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphical image on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much sold-out model, the work can be completed in a week, if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information in 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the fleet of vehicles running on the lanes, it is over 99%.
For the purpose of carrying out the documentation work and the production of databases, Audatex has eight distributed centers worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them has specialized in specific brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this huge flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the fault or residual value of a car.
The only company that provides information about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
When reviewing the products that Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the AudaPlus products being a standard solution for assessing accidents for the reviewers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid for according to the purpose of use, i.e. for each opinion.
The most expensive for customers who rarely use it will be a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, each insurance company that produces thousands of reviews negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly line, only on the basis of the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with vehicle windshields, and AudaSubastas is an online service that is open to the specialist market and can be used to offer vehicles that have been declared as total damage.
Your statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analyses or obtaining information about the deviations by brand and model.
For example, you can study how many models of a particular car brand had to go to the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes among others Gt Estimate, which is also intended for reviewers and provides the same way digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns and maintenance of vehicles.
The GT Guide for Testimonials is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 reviewers and 53 insurance companies.
In the last three years, its turnover has increased by 20% annually and in 2008 it generated sales of 10.8 million euros.
At the beginning of last year, they started to go to the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in 1966 in Germany and established in 1979 in Spain.
According to the company’s sources, 62% of its business is in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% is in North and South America, working with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
Total worldwide sales of the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amount to $557 million, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was valued at $1 billion on the stock exchange and today its shares are traded at $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, they have been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and part of the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
